social_posts.post_text: Some good old 1m days 🙃

Get them legs firing 🚀
1) ISO leg press holds pushing through your toes
2) Depth jumps with minimal ground contact time
3) KB squat jumps
4) KB swings
5) Deadlift
6) Penguin walk pushing through toes 🐧
And now for some 3m throwbacks 🤘🏼
🦾 Progress. 4 months and counting, time for some flips soon 🙃

And finally, those 10m days.. it’s crazy to think how 10m was the epitome of fear for me- just jumping, then learning voluntaries, and eventually optionals. No one learns a 10m list without smacking and/or hitting the platform (I was fortunate enough to do both :). So many ups and downs, battles fought and overcome. Plenty of blood, sweat, tears, bruises, and scars. And to think now 10m is just a low level line up and lead up platform, that diving almost 3x as high is standard, and how much I continue to grow and overcome. You’re more resilient and capable than you could ever imagine. Trust the process and keep pushing ⚡️

One year later and we’re back up top!

In August of last year, from a hospital bed in Innsbruck, I posted this excerpt from “The Obstacle Is The Way” by @ryanholiday 

“Our plans, even our bodies, can be broken. But belief in ourselves? No matter how many times we are thrown back, we alone retain the power to decide to go once more. Or to try another route. Or, at the very least, to accept this reality and decide upon a new aim. Determination, if you think about it, is invincible.”

It’s truly remarkable what we’re capable of with determination and hard work. No matter where you are or what obstacles you face, your best days are still ahead of you.

“Do not judge me by my successes, judge me by how many times I fell down and got back up.” -Nelson Mandela

A huge thanks to my team for patching my wing and getting me back in the air 🙏🏼 @eulersimon @patrickgrassnig @physio1.0 @amyschultz_pt @fionnmacpartlin @ireneoyang @gordhan.bm @redbullcliffdiving @bubsnaturals @missionviejonadadoresdive @drinknewmotion @area47 @ducko.us @usa_diving

🇯🇵 Yakushima Island and the Shiratani Unsui Gorge 🌲 This forest was absolutely magical with incredible trails, river crossings, moss covered trees and rocks, and an ancient, other worldly feel to it as we wandered around with no other humans in sight. If you’re ever in Japan I highly recommend adding this to the itinerary if you can fit it in as it was one of the highlights of my entire month there. It’s a shame our time on the island was cut short because of the incoming typhoon, but I’m glad we made it on the last flight leaving the island for 8 days!

🇯🇵 The hustle and bustle of Osaka has a fun sense of organized chaos to it as you meander the neighborhoods snacking and hopping around. Personally, takoyaki 🐙 isn’t for me 🤷🏼‍♂️ but I could eat yakiniku, ramen, and shushi every day 😋 Bar Nayuta was one of the best speakeasy / cocktail experiences I’ve had in a long time 🍸🍹 and catching our sea bass table side right before eating was an interesting dinner 🎣 Capped it off with a visit to the castle 🏰 and a local kendo tournament 🥷 for a solid visit to Japan’s third largest city.

The reverse somersault in three positions, “gainer three-po,” has always been one of my favorite cliff dives 🤘🏼 A new favorite of mine is @bubsnaturals Hydrate or Die electrolyte mix, which came in clutch during the hot, humid Japanese competitions 🥵 2000mg of powerful electrolytes with no junk and no added sugars 🙌🏼 Get yours along with a bunch of other great products 👉🏼 @bubsnaturals 💪🏼

🇯🇵 Kyoto! Favorites include the monkey park 🐒 Nishi Market with all kinds of delicious foods including the biggest pieces of nigiri I’ve ever seen 🍣 the botanical gardens and its incredible conservatory with diverse flora from all around the world 🌸 temples and shrines galore ⛩️ the bamboo forest 🎋 and Mister Gyoza! 🥟😋 

🤖 Also, not pictured, “GEAR” a unique non-verbal performance that stimulates your five senses with a moving story set in the future. Personified robots work in a former toy factory where a doll once manufactured by the factory suddenly appears. Through the slow comprehension and adaptation of the environment around them, Roboroids and Doll are able to obtain curiosity and playfulness, bringing them closer to human beings. Big thanks to @smeili_c for the recommendation 🙌🏼 definitely put it on your list if you can make it!

location.city_name: Nara Park 奈良公園, Nara Kōen Japan

social_posts.post_text: 🇯🇵 Nara Park 🦌 Where the deer flow like wine, and beautiful statues flock like the salmon of Capistrano 😜 but really, the park is gorgeous and fun to stroll around, and feeding / petting the deer is surreal. The statues in the Todai-ji Daibutsuden are extraordinarily impressive, and the spiritual connection and Buddhist vibes are visceral ✨

🇯🇵 Just a short train ride heading west from Shinjuku, you’ll find yourself on the edge of Chichibu-Tama-Kai National Park. With eight peaks over 2000m, and stunning views in every direction, including Mt Fuji to the south, this was one of our favorite day trips in Tokyo. It was hot and humid to start 🥵 like most summer days in Japan, but the breeze and cooler temperatures at elevation felt amazing. Varying terrain and diverse flora and fauna kept the hike interesting, a couple rope and chain ascents, and a spectacular view from the summit 🤩

🇯🇵 Ok, last Japan post I promise 😝 Tokyo is amazing, one of my favorite big cities. Delicious food, interesting culture, a diverse mix of people and activities, incredible architecture, a multitude of green spaces, convenient public transport, they really have it all 🙌🏼 Favorites include the Tsukiji Outer Market, Shinjuku National Garden 🌸 and teamLab museum ✨

Back to our regularly scheduled programming with beautiful summer days full of dome dips and twists at @area47 ☀️🙂🙃🙂

🚨NEW EPISODE ALERT🚨

Get ready to have some fun...

Today's guest is a great story teller and he shares some of his most epic stories with us in this episode!

Having started diving at the age of five, @dcolturi enjoyed some high-level success, and in 2009 he was the US National Champion in 10m platform individual and synchronized.

But he's forever thankful that he took a summer job in an amusement park after graduating from college. It was there, while working in a water stunt show, that he took his first dives from a 20-meter perch, and his passion for the sport he loved was reignited.

Despite having endured more than his fair share of injuries over the years competing from 27 meters (which is about 90 feet), David has been one of the standout cliff divers over the last decade.

He became the youngest ever winner of a World Series event at the age of 24, has earned 14 podium finishes and snagged a silver medal at the 2019 World Cup.

Away from cliff diving, Dave is forever on the lookout for new and stimulating activities, both mentally and physically. And you'll definitely hear him geek out about his passion for high performance in our conversation.

Listen close this episode because interwoven between the stories and the laughs is a ton of wisdom, experience and tools that you can use on your own journey.

You can listen directly on the website PursuitofGold.com or you can listen on your favorite podcast player.

Despite having endured more than his fair share of injuries over the years competing from 27 meters (which is about 90 feet), David has been one of the standout cliff divers over the last decade.

He became the youngest ever winner of a World Series event at the age of 24, has earned 14 podium finishes and snagged a silver medal at the 2019 World Cup.

Away from cliff diving, Dave is forever on the lookout for new and stimulating activities, both mentally and physically. And you'll definitely hear him geek out about his passion for high performance in our conversation.

Listen close this episode because interwoven between the stories and the laughs is a ton of wisdom, experience and tools that you can use on your own journey.

You can listen directly on the website PursuitofGold.com or you can listen on your favorite podcast player.
